flowRoot.flowPara: Select the desired gradient, Ctrl-C, then select the backgrounds and paste the style with Ctrl-Shift-V. Use the gradient tool to fit the gradient to the shapes.
You can, of course, make your own gradient. These are just meant to help you getting started.

Hit # to turn the grid on/off. Objects will snap to pixels when it's on. This produces sharper icons. Inkscape performance might be a bit bad though, so typing exact coordinates might be an alternative.
Open the 'Layers' dialog (Ctrl-Shift-L). Select the 'user icons' layer and paste/create your icon vector shape into it.
Hide the 'example icons layer' by clicking on the eye icon.
Duplicate your icon shape (Ctrl-D) to needed amount and move them to the icon background shapes. Scale them to about 85% of full size (in parenthesis) and tweak for sharpness.
There's an 'Icon Preview' on the 'View' menu that can help you getting sharp icons, but to get the default sizes 64 and 18 of Opera icons, you'll have to edit the preferences.xml of Inkscape.
This template has predefined slice shapes that must be perfectly aligned with the background shapes. Don't move either of these.
Copy a color gradient from the palette or make a new one. Paste to background shapes. Please try to be somewhat conservative in color choices.
To export icons, click the eye icon of the slices layer to make it visible. Click on the icon you want to export and hit 'Export Bitmap ..." (Ctrl-Shift-E). Repeat for all the needed icons.
